Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT Revenue Rises

PARAGRAPH.#text: Health Care REIT Inc. HCN said its fiscal first-quarter revenue rose due to stronger rental income and resident fees and services. Normalized funds from operations, a key performance metric for REITs, which exclude items such as transaction costs--improved to $1 a share from 91 cents, due to $3.6 billion of investments over the past 12 months and strong operating results. Analysts surveyed by Thomson Reuters recently forecast per-share FFO of 98 cents. The company raised its 2014 FFO guidance to $4.03 to $4.13 compared with the previous outlook of $3.93 to $4.03.

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Simon Property Names Mark Ordan as CEO of Planned Spinoff

PARAGRAPH.#text: Simon Property Group Inc. SPG named retail and retail-real-estate veteran Mark Ordan as the chief executive of the mall owner's planned Washington Prime Group Inc. spinoff. Most recently Mr. Ordan was chief executive of Sunrise Senior Living and led its turnaround and eventual sale to Health Care REIT Inc. HCN and KKR & Co. KKR. He also guided the turnaround at Mills Corp. and led its sale to Simon and Farallon Capital Management LLC. "We worked closely with Mark during the Mills transaction and found him to be a top-rate executive with particular expertise in creating value for an organization," Simon Chairman and CEO David Simon said in a news release.

Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT Expenses Obscure Jump in Revenue

PARAGRAPH.#text: Health Care REIT Inc. HCN said its fourth-quarter revenue jumped on robust rental income and fees, but earnings fell as expenses surged. Meanwhile, the company's normalized funds from operations--a key performance metric for REITs--topped expectations for the period. For the year, the company said it expects per-share normalized FFO to range from $3.53 to $3.63. Analysts polled by Thomson Reuters were expecting adjusted FFO of $4.02. Health Care REIT, one of the world's largest owners of senior housing, has relied heavily on acquisitions to broaden its property portfolio in recent years.

Headlines.Author: Anna Prior
Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT Buys Sunrise Senior for $845 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Anna Prior Health Care REIT Inc. HCN agreed to acquire Sunrise Senior Living Inc. SRZ in a deal that values the company at about $845 million and would make the health-care focused real-estate investment trust among the largest owners of seniors housing in the world. The deal, worth $14.50 a share, represents a premium of 62% to Sunrise's closing price Tuesday. Shares last traded above the offer price in fall 2008 but plunged to under 50 cents by the end of that year as concerns mounted that Sunrise might be forced to file for bankruptcy protection amid a mounting debt load.

Headlines.Author: Adam Edelman
Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT Prices 3M Shares At $41.44/Shr

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Health Care REIT Inc.

priced its underwritten public offering of 3 million common shares at $41.44 a share. Health Care expects about $124.3 million in gross proceeds from the offering and expects to use the net proceeds to invest in additional health care and senior housing properties. The offering is expected to close on March 10. The Toledo real estate investment trust announced the public offering Monday.

Headlines.Author: Freddy Sebastian
Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT Plans Offering Of 3M Shrs

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Health Care REIT Inc.

on Tuesday said it plans an offering of 3 million common shares, pending market and other conditions. The Toledo, Ohio, real estate investment trust said it will grant the underwriters, Deutsche Bank Securities and UBS Investment Bank, a 30-day option to purchase an additional 450,000 shares to cover over-allotments, if any. Health Care REIT intends to use the net proceeds of the offering to invest in additional properties.

Headlines.Headline: Health Care REIT 4Q Net More Than Doubles, Rev Jumps 56%

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Health Care REIT Inc.'s

fourth-quarter net income more than doubled, which the company attributed to its platform and infrastructure leveraging. The Toledo, Ohio, real estate investment trust's earnings rose to $48.9 million, or 52 cents a share, from $23 million, or 27 cents a share, a year earlier. Per-share funds from operations rose to 86 cents from 69 cents. Revenue jumped 56% to $133.5 million from $85.4 million a year ago.

Headlines.Headline: CFA 144a Conv Securities To Be Registered With The SEC

PARAGRAPH.#text: The following table is a list of Rule 144a privately issued convertible securities that are expected to be registered soon with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Privately issued securities generally are placed in a limited distribution to accredited investors or qualified institutional buyers before the securities are available to the public. Rule 144a of the Securities Act of 1933 provides that such securities are exempt from registration requirements. They may be initial or secondary offerings by a company and must be registered with the SEC before they are traded publicly.
